Key messages about waves:

1. The visual and auditory stimuli that we perceive occur in the form of waves;
2. Visual and auditory waves share similar physical properties; these properties influence how we perceive waves.

Key physical properties of waves that aid our understanding of waves and perception:

1. peak/crest of a wave: highest point on a wave (measured on a graph)
2. trough of a wave: lowest point of a wave (measured on a graph)
3. amplitude: the height of the wave, measured from peak to trough
4. wavelength: length of the wave from peak to peak
5. frequency: number of waves that pass a given point in a given time period (unit=hertz, Hz). Frequency and wavelength are inversely related - higher frequencies have shorter wavelengths and lower frequencies have longer wavelengths

Light waves and perception: 

1. Perception of light waves can be understood through the electromagnetic spectrum, which includes all of the electromagnetic radiation that occurs in our environment and is measured as wavelengths, in nanometres (nm);
2.  Parts of the electromagnetic spectrum include radiowaves (the longest wavelength with the lowest frequency) and gamma rays (the shortest wavelengths with the highest frequency);
3. One part of the electromagnetic spectrum for humans is what we call the "visible spectrum" - this is what humans can perceive through sight. This is one small part of this spectrum (380-740nm);
4. Other animals have different "visible spectrums" - for example, honeybees see light in the ultraviolet radiation range and some snakes detect infrared radiation range;
5. For humans, different wavelengths within the visible spectrum are associated with the perception of different colours; 
6. For humans, wavelength follows a rainbow pattern, with the largest half-circle of the rainbow (red, ~740nm) having longer wavelengths (and shorter frequencies) and the smallest half-circle in the rainbow (violet, ~380nm) having shorter wavelengths (and higher frequencies).

Sound waves and perception: 

1. Perception of sound waves can be understood through two physical properties of waves: frequency and loudness; 
2.  Frequency is associated with our perception of “pitch” – higher frequency sound waves are associated with high-pitched sounds, and lower frequency sound waves are associated with low-pitched sounds;
3. For humans, the “audible range” of frequencies are those that humans perceive through hearing (20-20,000 Hz). This is one small part of the overall range of sounds that occur in our environments;
4. Other animals have different "audible ranges" - for example, dogs and cats can hear sounds between 70-45,000 Hz nd 45-64,000 Hz; 
5. The amplitudes of sound waves are also another way to measure how sounds are perceived. Higher amplitudes of waves are associated with louder sounds, while shorter amplitudes are associated with quieter sounds. Loudness is measured in decibals (dB);
6. For humans, the quietest noises we can generally hear are around 30dB (e.g., rustling of leaves), and there is the potential for hearing damage from about 80-130dB (e.g., subway train at 20ft away, jackhammer);
7. Frequency and amplitude of sounds can interact to affect how we perceive sounds: for example, no matter how high the amplitude of a 10 Hz sound wave is, we cannot perceive it.
